(290, 'throwawaymedia', 30189669, NULL, '2022-02-03 08:21:25', 'There are a lot of professional workers that are on cocaine, business owners, successful artists, etc. Does that mean cocaine should be legalized? Absolutely not.<p>Marijuana as a prescription is perfectly cool, whereas legal public marijuana smoking is a pure nonsense.<p>(a) There are tons of research papers on marijuana being harmful to your brain.<p>(b) The smell of marijuana is the worst. It spreads like cancer and you can smell it blocks away.<p>(c) Uneducated people start from marijuana and then look for other &quot;fun&quot; things to smoke.<p>My brother-in-law started from smoking marijuana when he was young. At 20-something he switched to pills, a few more years later - heroine. He died when he was 34.<p>In contrast, the majority of anti-vaxxers (not the crazy ones talking about microchips) ended up being more or less right with their decision. Many research papers confirm that the vaccine is the most beneficial to older population. When it comes to younger people, doesn&#x27;t matter much, you won&#x27;t die from COVID, chances of side effects are very slim, natural anti-bodies are more flexible when it comes to various virus variants (according to a paper in Nature). Several countries have already dropped ALL the mandates, lock-downs, vaccine passports, etc and prefer natural immunity.', 'comment', NULL, NULL, NULL, 30189189, 'None', NULL, NULL, 0),
(291, 'yitchelle', 30189670, NULL, '2022-02-03 08:21:25', 'I have tried Lunchclub. I liked the fact that it relies its user base with work and professional background. However once the initial contact is made, ongoing conversation rarely took place.\nHope this solves the problem of ongoing conversation.', 'comment', NULL, NULL, NULL, 30179355, 'None', NULL, NULL, 0),
(292, 'dredmorbius', 30189671, NULL, '2022-02-03 08:21:30', 'The theory in the US is of a separation of powers, and a devolution of powers from the Constitution.<p><a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;en.wikipedia.org&#x2F;wiki&#x2F;Separation_of_powers_under_the_United_States_Constitution\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;en.wikipedia.org&#x2F;wiki&#x2F;Separation_of_powers_under_the...</a><p>The three branches of the US government are the Legislative, which creates law, the Executive, which enacts and enforces it, and the Judiciary, which judges it.<p>Their powers and limitations are in part set out in the US Constitution, though major doctrines, e.g., the US Supreme Court&#x27;s power of judicial review, and the ability to declare statutory law unconstitutional, are established by precedent and practice (in this case, Marbury vs. Madison, see:  <a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;en.wikipedia.org&#x2F;wiki&#x2F;Marbury_v._Madison\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;en.wikipedia.org&#x2F;wiki&#x2F;Marbury_v._Madison</a>).<p>In short:<p>- The President (head of the Executive Branch) can only act within the framework of laws passed by Congress.  There is executive law, in the form of the Code of Federal Regulations, which is generally drafted by federal agencies, but it is secondary to the <i>statutory</i> law.  <a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;www.archives.gov&#x2F;federal-register&#x2F;cfr&#x2F;about.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;www.archives.gov&#x2F;federal-register&#x2F;cfr&#x2F;about.html</a>  The President also has power of appointments, pardons, and leading the armed forces, but <i>not</i> declaration of war.<p>- Congress passes legislation, <i>statutory law</i>, known as the United States Code, or USC.  <a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;uscode.house.gov&#x2F;\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;uscode.house.gov&#x2F;</a>   This is the principle power of Congress, though it also has the power to approve or deny appointments, and to hear impeachments, as well as to declare war and ratify treaties.<p>- The Judiciary as noted both hears cases and provides judicial review over law.<p>All three branches have their powers defined in the US Constitution and its amendments.<p>TL;DR:  He cannot, the US presidency is powerful, but still limited.  Laws passed by Congress must be either rescinded by Congress or invalidated by the Court.  Though there is probably some creative executive action which might be possible, and ... could be interesting to contemplate.', 'comment', NULL, NULL, NULL, 30187938, 'None', NULL, NULL, 0),
